Section 1 — Threat overview (the hero)
The first thing a user sees. One big risk score (0–100) in a ring gauge, a plain-English verdict ("HIGH BEHAVIORAL RISK DETECTED"), and 3 badge pills summarizing the key findings. This is the "TL;DR" of the entire scan — judges should be able to understand the danger in 5 seconds.
Section 2 — Metric cards (6 KPIs)
Quick-glance numbers: total commits scanned, suspicious commits, flagged contributors, at-risk files, total contributors, and the overall risk score. Each number gets a label and a small context hint below it.
Section 3 — Risk dimension breakdown + commit activity chart
Two columns side by side. Left: horizontal bar chart breaking the overall risk score into 7 specific dimensions (commit behavior, code injection, contributor trust, binary blobs, issue patterns, build script risk, PR bypass). Right: an 18-month activity timeline bar chart where flagged weeks glow red — instantly shows "when did things go wrong."
Section 4 — Flagged commits table
Every suspicious commit in a row: hash, author, message, and a short danger tag (BACKDOOR PATTERN, BINARY INJECTION, MASKING PATTERN). Each row is clickable — pressing it sends the commit details to the AI for a deeper explanation. This is the most actionable section.
Section 5 — Contributor risk profiles
Each contributor as a card with an avatar/initials, join date, commit count, trust score, behavioral stats (off-hours %, average commit time), and a color-coded trust bar. New contributors with suspicious patterns get a CRITICAL badge; established ones with clean history get TRUSTED.
Section 6 — Vulnerable code hotspots
The actual files that are dangerous, with the specific line ranges flagged, a mini risk bar, and a severity badge. This tells the developer exactly where to look in the codebase.
Section 7 — AI detection signals
Six cards showing the specific machine-learning signals that triggered the alert — things like "binary payload injection," "off-hours commit clustering," "social engineering pattern," "build script manipulation." Each has a colored indicator and a 2-line explanation in plain English.
Section 8 — Gemini LLM explanation
A terminal-style text box where the LLM converts all the raw signals into a narrative paragraph that a non-technical person (like a judge, or a manager) can understand. This is the "explain it to me like I'm 5" layer.
Section 9 — Security recommendations
Ranked action items: CRITICAL (do now), HIGH (do this week), RECOMMENDED (best practice). Each has an icon, priority label, and a specific instruction. Not vague advice — concrete steps.
Section 10 — Action buttons
Export Report, Enable Monitoring, Deep Dive, View CVE — these are the next-step CTAs. For judges these show the product has a clear user journey beyond just showing results. Sonnet 4.6Extended
